    review: "Fyodor Dostoevsky's Crime and Punishment is the novel that taught literature how to think about the interior life of a person in crisis. Published in 1866, it follows Rodion Raskolnikov, a destitute former law student in St. Petersburg, who convinces himself that he has the intellectual and moral right to murder a predatory pawnbroker — and then spends the remainder of the novel being psychologically annihilated by the act.\n\nWhat makes Raskolnikov's crime so terrifying is that his reasoning is not absurd. He constructs a utilitarian argument — one worthless life taken to fund a brilliant career that will benefit thousands — that is internally coherent. Dostoevsky's genius is to show that intellectual coherence is not the same as moral truth. The theory works on paper. It disintegrates on contact with a human skull and a hatchet.\n\nThe novel's greatness lies in its psychological architecture. Raskolnikov oscillates between grandiose confession and paranoid concealment, between desperate self-justification and involuntary acts of compassion. The detective Porfiry Petrovich is one of literature's great antagonists — a man who solves the crime not through evidence but through conversation, slowly tightening a noose made entirely of Raskolnikov's own words.\n\nSonya Marmeladova, the prostitute whose faith Raskolnikov cannot understand but cannot dismiss, represents Dostoevsky's counter-argument to rationalist nihilism: that suffering, freely accepted and shared, is the only path to redemption. It is an argument that requires a leap of faith the novel does not make easy.\n\nCrime and Punishment is not comfortable reading. It is reading that changes the shape of your thinking about conscience, freedom, and the cost of believing yourself exceptional.",
