    review: "Miguel de Cervantes published the first part of Don Quixote in 1605 and the second in 1615. In doing so, he invented the modern novel. This is not a metaphor or an exaggeration — it is a statement of literary fact. Before Cervantes, prose fiction was romance, allegory, or chronicle. After Cervantes, it was possible for a fictional character to be aware of his own fictionality, for a novel to critique its own genre, and for comedy and tragedy to inhabit the same sentence.\n\nThe premise is famous: Alonso Quixano, a minor Spanish hidalgo, reads so many chivalric romances that he loses his mind and sets out as a knight-errant, renaming himself Don Quixote de la Mancha. He tilts at windmills, attacks flocks of sheep, and mistakes inns for castles. His squire, Sancho Panza — a peasant of magnificent common sense and gradually expanding wisdom — follows him out of loyalty, greed, and something that eventually reveals itself as love.\n\nIn Part One, the comedy is primarily external: the gap between Quixote's delusions and reality is the source of humor. But in Part Two — written ten years later, after an unauthorized sequel by another author — Cervantes achieves something unprecedented. Characters within the novel have read Part One. They recognize Quixote. They stage elaborate performances to manipulate him. The knight's madness is no longer a private delusion but a public spectacle, and the cruelty of that spectacle becomes the novel's devastating moral subject.\n\nQuixote's final defeat is one of the most heartbreaking moments in literature. He regains his sanity, renounces his knightly identity, and dies as Alonso Quixano — sane, ordinary, and diminished. Sancho begs him to continue the adventure. The reader, against all reason, agrees with Sancho. We have come to love the madness because the madness contained the only genuine nobility in a cynical world.\n\nEvery great novelist — Fielding, Flaubert, Dostoevsky, Borges, Nabokov — writes in the shadow of Cervantes. Don Quixote is not merely the first novel. It remains one of the greatest.",
