    theBad: "The nested narrative structure — a story within a story within a story — creates deliberate distance that can frustrate readers seeking direct emotional access.",
    review: "Emily Brontë published one novel, died at thirty, and left behind a work that remains one of the most singular and disturbing achievements in the English language. Wuthering Heights, published in 1847 under the pseudonym Ellis Bell, is not a romance. It is a novel about what happens when love operates with the same indifferent, destructive force as weather.\n\nHeathcliff and Catherine Earnshaw are not star-crossed lovers in any conventional sense. Their attachment is pre-social, pre-moral, almost pre-human. Catherine's famous declaration — 'I am Heathcliff' — is not romantic hyperbole but a statement of ontological fact. They are the same substance. When Catherine marries Edgar Linton for social respectability, she does not betray Heathcliff; she betrays the fundamental nature of her own being. The rest of the novel is the catastrophic consequence.\n\nHeathcliff's revenge is not the refined scheming of a Byronic hero. It is systematic, patient, and shockingly cruel. He destroys two families across two generations — the Earnshaws and the Lintons — through property manipulation, forced marriages, and psychological abuse. Brontë does not ask us to sympathize with Heathcliff. She asks us to witness the damage that thwarted passion can inflict when it has no outlet except destruction.\n\nThe novel's formal structure is as wild as its content. The story is narrated by Nelly Dean, a servant of limited perspective, to Mr. Lockwood, a tenant of even more limited understanding. The effect is that the most extreme emotions in English fiction are filtered through the most ordinary consciousness. This disjunction creates a vertiginous effect — we are always hearing about events that exceed our narrator's capacity to comprehend them.\n\nBrontë's prose channels the Yorkshire landscape into syntax: harsh, exposed, magnificent. The moors are not a backdrop; they are a character, the medium through which Heathcliff and Catherine's bond is expressed. The novel begins and ends with images of the moors at rest — but between those images lies a tempest that has no equivalent in English fiction.\n\nWuthering Heights was misunderstood and condemned upon publication. It has outlasted every novel that was praised in its place.",
