    review: "Albert Camus's The Stranger is a novel of terrifying compression. Published in 1942 in occupied France, it tells the story of Meursault, a French Algerian clerk who attends his mother's funeral without crying, begins a casual love affair the next day, and then, on a sun-blasted beach, shoots and kills an Arab man for no discernible reason. He is arrested, tried, and condemned — not for the murder, but for his failure to cry at his mother's funeral.\n\nThe novel's opening line — 'Mother died today. Or maybe yesterday; I can't be sure' — establishes Meursault's radical honesty. He is not a sociopath; he is a man who refuses to perform the emotional rituals that society demands. He will not pretend to grieve more than he grieves. He will not pretend to love more than he loves. He will not fabricate meaning where he perceives none. This refusal is his crime.\n\nCamus's prose style — flat, declarative, shorn of metaphor — is the perfect vehicle for Meursault's consciousness. The sentences are simple. The observations are sensory. The sun, the sea, the heat — these are not symbols but physical realities that press on Meursault with oppressive force. The murder itself is described with the same detached precision as the preparation of a meal.\n\nThe trial is the novel's satirical core. The prosecutor constructs a narrative of Meursault as a moral monster — a man who smoked at his mother's vigil, who went swimming the next day, who watched a comedy film. The jury convicts him not for killing a man but for failing to conform to the social contract of performed emotion. Camus's point is devastating: society would rather forgive a murderer who weeps than tolerate an honest man who does not.\n\nThe final pages, in which Meursault confronts the prison chaplain and opens himself to 'the gentle indifference of the world,' constitute one of the great philosophical passages in fiction. Meursault achieves not resignation but liberation — a fierce, joyful acceptance of a universe without inherent meaning.\n\nThe Stranger is the founding document of absurdist literature. It is short, cold, and absolutely unforgettable.",
