    review: "Virginia Woolf's Mrs Dalloway unfolds across a single day in June 1923, as Clarissa Dalloway, the wife of a Member of Parliament, prepares for a party she is hosting that evening. In that day, Woolf contains an entire world: the lingering trauma of the Great War, the rigid class structure of interwar London, the secret history of a woman's unlived life, and the question of what makes a single human existence meaningful.\n\nThe novel's formal innovation is its seamless movement between consciousnesses. Woolf passes from Clarissa's mind to the mind of a stranger on the street, from Peter Walsh's memories to the delusions of Septimus Warren Smith — a shell-shocked veteran who serves as Clarissa's dark double. There are no chapter breaks, no section headers. Consciousness flows like the London traffic Woolf describes: continuous, unpredictable, alive.\n\nClarissa Dalloway is a woman of surfaces — charming, proper, socially adept — but Woolf reveals the depths beneath. Clarissa's memory of kissing Sally Seton as a young woman — 'the most exquisite moment of her whole life' — is rendered with such delicate intensity that it restructures everything we understand about her marriage, her choices, and her regrets. Woolf never names what Clarissa has sacrificed; she simply shows us the shape of the absence.\n\nSeptimus Warren Smith, the traumatized veteran who cannot stop seeing his dead friend Evans, provides the novel's moral and political weight. His treatment by the medical establishment — Dr. Holmes's breezy dismissal, Sir William Bradshaw's authoritarian 'sense of proportion' — is Woolf's indictment of a society that sends its young men to die and then punishes them for being damaged. Septimus's suicide, when it arrives, is both horrifying and logical.\n\nThe party scene that closes the novel is one of Woolf's supreme achievements. Clarissa learns of Septimus's death from a guest, and in a moment of extraordinary empathic connection, she understands — across class, across experience, across the unbridgeable gulf of another's suffering — what his death meant. 'She felt somehow very like him,' Woolf writes. It is a moment of grace that justifies the entire novel.\n\nMrs Dalloway is a novel about the courage required simply to go on living. It is one of the greatest novels of the twentieth century.",
