    review: "Mary Shelley was eighteen years old when she began writing Frankenstein, nineteen when she finished it, and twenty when it was published anonymously in 1818. It is the most remarkable debut in the history of English literature, and it invented an entire genre — science fiction — two centuries before the term existed.\n\nThe novel's premise is universally known but almost universally misunderstood. Victor Frankenstein, a young Swiss scientist, creates a living being from dead matter. Horrified by his creation's appearance, he abandons it. The Creature — intelligent, sensitive, desperately lonely — is rejected by every human it encounters and eventually turns to violence. The novel is not about a monster. It is about a father who refuses to love his child.\n\nShelley's great insight is that monstrosity is not innate but manufactured. The Creature is born innocent. It learns language by secretly observing a family through a crack in a wall. It reads Milton, Plutarch, and Goethe. It is capable of extraordinary tenderness. But every attempt it makes to connect with humanity is met with screaming, violence, and rejection. The Creature becomes a murderer not because it is evil but because it has been taught — by its creator and by society — that it is unworthy of love.\n\nVictor Frankenstein is the novel's true monster: a man of enormous intellectual ambition and catastrophic moral cowardice. He creates life and then refuses responsibility for it. He allows an innocent woman to be executed for a murder his creation committed. He is warned repeatedly and does nothing. Shelley's portrait of male scientific hubris — the Promethean drive to create without considering the consequences of creation — remains the foundational critique of technological irresponsibility.\n\nThe novel's nested narrative structure — Walton's letters containing Frankenstein's story containing the Creature's story — mirrors the layers of creation and interpretation that are its subject. Who is telling the truth? Whose suffering is more legitimate? Shelley refuses to adjudicate.\n\nFrankenstein is a novel about the ethics of creation, the politics of appearance, and the catastrophic consequences of abandonment. That it was written by a teenager, during a rainy summer in Geneva, remains one of literature's most extraordinary facts.",
