    review: "F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby is the American novel distilled to its purest essence: 180 pages about money, love, class, and the fatal enchantment of the past. Published in 1925 to modest sales and mixed reviews, it was canonized posthumously and now stands as the most taught, most analyzed, and most argued-over novel in American secondary education. All of that institutional weight can obscure what makes it genuinely great: the prose.\n\nFitzgerald writes sentences of heartbreaking beauty. The green light at the end of Daisy's dock. The eyes of Doctor T. J. Eckleburg staring from a faded billboard over the valley of ashes. Gatsby's shirts, cascading from his closet while Daisy weeps — not from love, but from the overwhelming material proof that Gatsby has succeeded in becoming something she once thought impossible. Every image in this novel carries the weight of an entire argument about American civilization.\n\nJay Gatsby is the American Dream made flesh — and the novel's subject is the moment that flesh begins to rot. Gatsby has reinvented himself from James Gatz, a poor North Dakota farm boy, into a fabulously wealthy Long Island bootlegger, all in pursuit of a single goal: to recapture a love affair with Daisy Buchanan that lasted one month five years ago. His tragedy is not that he fails but that his success is impossible by definition. He wants to repeat the past. Nick Carraway tells him he can't. 'Can't repeat the past?' Gatsby replies. 'Why of course you can!' He is wrong. That wrongness is the novel's entire moral architecture.\n\nNick Carraway's narration is the novel's most sophisticated formal achievement. Nick is both inside and outside the world he describes — midwestern enough to be appalled by East Egg's carelessness, romantic enough to be seduced by Gatsby's capacity for wonder. His famous final assessment of Gatsby — 'He was worth the whole damn bunch put together' — is both a moral judgment and an admission of complicity. Nick admires what he knows he should condemn.\n\nThe novel's last paragraph — 'So we beat on, boats against the current, borne back ceaselessly into the past' — is the most famous ending in American literature, and it earns every syllable of its fame. Fitzgerald captures, in a single image, the tragedy of American aspiration: we reach for the future but are pulled backward by the gravitational force of everything we have already lost.\n\nThe Great Gatsby is a small, perfect novel about the largest American subject. It is inescapable.",
